{"badges":["TM5","TM6"],"usefulItems":"champagne flutes","id":"r71005","imageLink":"https:\/\/2.bp.blogspot.com\/-EraJtK34JiE\/XZXYuAaauWI\/AAAAAAAAgBI\/SSvm3xCj3AIY74Wh4C9c5mJ8UOlWe_UNgCLcBGAsYHQ\/s1600\/0_SW5Js6huW-Sk06lO.png","title":"Peach Bellini","publishedAt":"2015-08-07T00:00:00Z","ingredients":[{"content":"250 g peaches, peeled and stones removed or 400 g canned peaches drained (approx. 260 g after draining)"},{"content":"30 - 50 g caster sugar, to taste"},{"content":"750 g white sparkling wine (1 bottle), chilled"}],"nutrition":{"protein":"0.7 g","fat":"0.04 g","uom":"per 1 portion","carbohydrates":"13.7 g","calories":"359 kJ \/ 85 kcal"},"preparations":[{"content":"Place peaches and sugar into mixing bowl and blend <b>30 sec\/speed 9<b>, or until a smooth consistency is achieved. Scrape down sides of mixing bowl with spatula."},{"content":"Add 100 g of the sparkling wine and blend <b>5 sec\/speed 4<b>."},{"content":"Distribute peach mixture between 6 chilled champagne flutes and top with remaining sparkling wine. Stir to combine and serve immediately."}],"hintsAndTricks":["#The Bellini is believed to have been created between 1934 and 1948, by Giuseppe Cipriani. The drink was named after the Venetian artist Giovanni Bellini, when the unique pink hue of the cocktail reminded Ciprani of the toga worn by a saint in one of the artist's paintings. Ever since, the drink has been known as the 'Bellini'.<br>#"],"basicInfo":["easy","5m","5m","6 portions"]}